<HEADLINE>
MASTER'S DEGREE HOLDERS HAVE LOWER SALARY OFFERS THAN EXPECTED
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March  3 (CNA) 03/03/07  18:52:25 (By Elizabeth Hsu)
</P>
<P>
The average monthly wage demanded by soon-to-graduate master's
degree holders appears to be more than NT$6,000 (US$182) higher
than the average offered by employers, according to the results
of a survey released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Job seekers  about to graduate  from advanced  educational
institutes in the middle of this year are demanding an monthly
salary of NT$37,600 on average, while the enterprises are
offering only NT$31,092, according to the results of the survey
conducted by the Web-based 104 Job Bank Corp. among so-called
"social freshmen."
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that 90 percent of military draftees due to
end their service this year, as well as nearly half of the
prospective graduates, have begun looking for jobs.
</P>
<P>
The electronics and information sectors are the top choice, with
30.2 percent of the job seekers scouting these sectors, while
11.5 percent have applied to work in firms in the sectors of
finance, investment consultancy and insurance, 10.2 percent in
the service sector and 8.1 percent in the sport and leisure
business.
</P>
<P>
Jobs in the professional fields of finance, information and
computer software, administration and legal affairs, as well as
marketing, business planning and management, are the most
popular.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, enterprises around the country are
offering some 100,000 job vacancies for the new graduates with
little or no work experience, with 29.1 percent of the jobs
provided by businesses in the electronics and information
sectors, followed by 13.2 percent in the traditional
manufacturing industry and 12.7 percent in the sectors of
finance, investment consultancy and insurance.
</P>
<P>
The most common job offerings are in sales,  followed by
engineering research and operating technician.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that new graduates from universities or
colleges expect an average monthly salary of NT$26,530, while the
job providers are promising an average starting salary of
NT$28,212.
</P>
<P>
104 Job Bank Chairman Rocky Yang said more and more people
believe they cannot find a "good" job or a well-paid job without
a master's degree. However, despite the number of post-graduate
students increasing, the quality of manpower has not increased,
Yang said.
</P>
